## 🧩 4. Minimum Time to Infect All Servers (Graph + BFS)

### 📌 Problem
A failure starts from a given server and spreads to directly connected servers every second.

Given:
- `n` servers labeled from 1 to n
- `connections` (bidirectional edges)
- `start` node

Return:
- Minimum time to infect all servers
- `-1` if not all servers can be reached

---

### 🧠 Key Idea
- Represent as a graph
- Use BFS (level-order traversal)
- Each level = 1 second

---

### ✅ Approach
1. Build adjacency list  
2. BFS from `start`  
3. Track visited nodes  
4. Count levels (time)  
5. If any node is unvisited → return -1  

---

### 💻 Code

```java
import java.util.*;

class Solution {
    public int minTimeToInfect(int n, int[][] connections, int start) {

        Map<Integer, List<Integer>> graph = new HashMap<>();

        for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
            graph.put(i, new ArrayList<>());
        }

        for (int[] edge : connections) {
            graph.get(edge[0]).add(edge[1]);
            graph.get(edge[1]).add(edge[0]);
        }

        Queue<Integer> queue = new LinkedList<>();
        boolean[] visited = new boolean[n + 1];

        queue.add(start);
        visited[start] = true;

        int time = -1;

        while (!queue.isEmpty()) {
            int size = queue.size();
            time++;

            for (int i = 0; i < size; i++) {
                int node = queue.poll();

                for (int nei : graph.get(node)) {
                    if (!visited[nei]) {
                        visited[nei] = true;
                        queue.add(nei);
                    }
                }
            }
        }

        for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
            if (!visited[i]) return -1;
        }

        return time;
    }
}
❌ Mistakes Made
Didn’t build adjacency list
Wrong BFS traversal logic
Incremented time per node instead of per level
🎯 Pattern

Graph + BFS (Level Order Traversal)

🧩 5. Task Scheduler (Greedy + Frequency)
📌 Problem

Tasks must be executed with cooldown n.

Same task must wait n seconds before reuse.

Return minimum time required to finish all tasks.

🧠 Key Idea
Most frequent task determines schedule
Use mathematical formula instead of simulation
✅ Approach
Count frequency of tasks
Find:
maxFreq = highest frequency
maxCount = number of tasks with that frequency
Apply formula:
(maxFreq - 1) * (n + 1) + maxCount
Final result:
max(totalTasks, formula)
💻 Code
import java.util.*;

class Solution {
    public int leastInterval(char[] tasks, int n) {

        int[] freq = new int[26];

        for (char c : tasks) {
            freq[c - 'A']++;
        }

        int maxFreq = 0;
        for (int f : freq) {
            maxFreq = Math.max(maxFreq, f);
        }

        int maxCount = 0;
        for (int f : freq) {
            if (f == maxFreq) maxCount++;
        }

        int result = (maxFreq - 1) * (n + 1) + maxCount;

        return Math.max(tasks.length, result);
    }
}
❌ Mistakes Made
Tried full simulation
Didn’t identify dominant task
Missed final max() logic
🎯 Pattern

Greedy + Frequency Counting

🧩 6. Suspicious File Access (Sliding Window + Set)
📌 Problem

A user is suspicious if:

Accesses at least 3 distinct files
Within any 300-second window
🧠 Key Idea
Group logs per user
Sort by time
Use sliding window + set for distinct tracking
✅ Approach
Map user → list of (time, file)
Sort by time
Use sliding window:
Expand right pointer
Shrink left pointer if time difference > 300
Maintain a set of distinct files
If set size ≥ 3 → mark user
💻 Code
import java.util.*;

class Solution {

    class Pair {
        int time;
        String file;

        Pair(int time, String file) {
            this.time = time;
            this.file = file;
        }
    }

    public List<String> findSuspiciousUsers(String[] logs) {

        Map<String, List<Pair>> map = new HashMap<>();

        for (String log : logs) {
            String[] parts = log.split(" ");
            String user = parts[0];
            String file = parts[1];
            int time = Integer.parseInt(parts[2]);

            map.putIfAbsent(user, new ArrayList<>());
            map.get(user).add(new Pair(time, file));
        }

        List<String> result = new ArrayList<>();

        for (String user : map.keySet()) {

            List<Pair> list = map.get(user);
            Collections.sort(list, (a, b) -> a.time - b.time);

            int left = 0;
            Set<String> set = new HashSet<>();

            for (int right = 0; right < list.size(); right++) {

                set.add(list.get(right).file);

                while (list.get(right).time - list.get(left).time > 300) {
                    set.remove(list.get(left).file);
                    left++;
                }

                if (set.size() >= 3) {
                    result.add(user);
                    break;
                }
            }
        }

        Collections.sort(result);
        return result;
    }
}
❌ Mistakes Made
Used counting instead of distinct tracking
Missed sliding window logic
Didn’t handle time constraint correctly
🎯 Pattern

Sliding Window + Set + Sorting

